import{a as e}from"./chunk-3ZME3H5X.js";import"./chunk-IFGU66OU.js";var t={meta:e,sections:[{id:"overview",title:"Overview",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'X (formerly Twitter) is a real-time, public **social broadcast** network: users post short messages ("tweets"/"posts"), follow others, and read a **home timeline** blending posts from everyone they follow. It serves **~500M+ users** and **hundreds of millions of posts/day**, with reads outnumbering writes by **~100:1**. The defining challenge is assembling a fresh, ranked home timeline for every user, fast, despite a massively skewed follower graph.'},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"The big idea",body:"The home timeline is the crux. Computing it on every read (merge the latest posts from everyone you follow) is too slow at scale. Precomputing it on every write (push each post into all followers' timelines) is too expensive for **celebrities** with 100M+ followers. The real system is a **hybrid fan-out**: push for normal users, pull-and-merge for the few accounts with enormous reach."},{type:"image",src:"assets/diagrams/twitter-timeline.svg",alt:"X home timeline architecture: author posts via the write path which persists to the tweet store and fans out tweet IDs into per-user Redis timeline caches; celebrity posts are merged at read time; the reader fetches the precomputed timeline.",caption:"Hybrid timeline construction. Most posts are fanned out to follower timeline caches on write; high-fan-out (celebrity) posts are merged in at read time."}]},{id:"functional-requirements",title:"Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"We scope the interview to the social/timeline core."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"In scope",practices:["**Post a tweet** (text up to 280 chars, optional media, links).","**Follow / unfollow** users (the social graph).","**Home timeline**: ranked feed of posts from followed accounts.","**User timeline**: a single user's own posts (profile page).","**Engagement**: like, reply, repost (retweet), quote.","**Search** posts and users; **trending** topics.","**Notifications** for mentions, likes, follows."]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Out of scope (state this explicitly)",body:"DMs (a separate messaging system \u2014 see the WhatsApp design), ads/monetization, the full ML ranking model, live video, and Spaces. Calling out the boundary keeps the focus on the timeline + graph."}]},{id:"non-functional-requirements",title:"Non-Functional Requirements",blocks:[{type:"prosCons",title:"Prioritizing the qualities",pros:["Low read latency: home timeline in < 200ms (it is the core experience).","High availability for reads (target 99.99%) \u2014 a broken timeline is very visible.","Read-heavy horizontal scalability (~100:1 read:write).","Reasonable freshness: new posts appear within seconds.","Durable writes: an accepted post is never lost."],cons:["Strong global consistency is NOT required \u2014 eventual is fine for feeds.","A few seconds of timeline staleness is acceptable.","Exact real-time like/repost counts are not critical (approximate is ok)."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"CAP framing",body:"Overwhelmingly **AP** for the read path. If a follower's timeline is briefly missing the very latest post, that is acceptable; an unavailable home feed is not. Counts (likes/reposts/views) are eventually-consistent approximations served from counters, not transactional reads."}]},{id:"capacity-estimation",title:"Capacity Estimation",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Assume **500M** total users, **250M** daily active, **400M** posts/day, and an average of **~200 followers** per user (heavily skewed \u2014 most have few, a handful have 100M+)."},{type:"metrics",items:[{label:"Daily active users",value:"~250M",hint:"DAU"},{label:"Posts / day",value:"~400M",hint:"~4,600/sec avg"},{label:"Peak posts / sec",value:"~15k+",hint:"events / breaking news"},{label:"Timeline reads / sec",value:"~500k+",hint:"read-heavy ~100:1"},{label:"Avg followers",value:"~200",hint:"median far lower"},{label:"Fan-out writes / sec",value:"~1M+",hint:"posts \xD7 followers"}]},{type:"markdown",value:"The number that dictates the architecture is **fan-out write amplification** \u2014 one post can generate millions of timeline writes:"},{type:"math",display:!0,tex:"W_{fanout} = P_{sec} \\times F_{avg} = 4{,}600\\ \\text{posts/s} \\times 200\\ \\text{followers} \\approx 9.2\\times10^{5}\\ \\text{timeline writes/s}",caption:"Average fan-out write load. A single celebrity post (100M followers) would alone create 100M writes \u2014 which is exactly why pure fan-out-on-write fails for them."},{type:"markdown",value:"Storage for posts is modest (text is small); the expensive store is the **timeline cache** (hundreds of millions of per-user lists of recent tweet IDs) and the **social graph** (billions of follow edges)."}]},{id:"high-level-architecture",title:"High-Level Architecture",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Writes go through a Tweet Service that persists the post and emits a fan-out event. **Fan-out workers** push the new tweet ID into each follower's Redis timeline. Reads hit the Timeline Service, which returns the precomputed list of IDs, **hydrates** them with tweet content, **merges** in any celebrity posts, ranks, and returns."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Write path (fan-out) and read path (hydrate + merge + rank).",definition:`flowchart TD
  Author["Author"] -->|POST /tweet| TweetSvc["Tweet Service"]
  TweetSvc --> Store[("Tweet Store: Manhattan/Cassandra")]
  TweetSvc --> Kafka[("Kafka: tweet.created")]
  Kafka --> Fanout["Fan-out Workers"]
  Graph[("Social Graph: follower lists")] --> Fanout
  Fanout --> TL[("Timeline Cache: Redis per-user")]
  Reader["Reader"] -->|GET /home| TimelineSvc["Timeline Service"]
  TL --> TimelineSvc
  Store --> TimelineSvc
  Celeb["Celebrity posts (pull)"] --> TimelineSvc
  TimelineSvc --> Rank["Ranking / ML"]
  Rank --> Reader`},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Fan-out Service",description:"Consumes tweet.created events, looks up the author's followers in the social graph, and writes the tweet ID into each follower's Redis timeline (capped to the most recent ~800). Skips fan-out for high-follower accounts (handled at read time).",icon:"network",tags:["fan-out-on-write","kafka","async"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Timeline Service",description:"On read, fetches the precomputed list of tweet IDs from Redis, hydrates them with content + author + engagement counts, merges in celebrity posts pulled at read time, applies ranking, and returns a page.",icon:"layers",tags:["read-path","hydrate","merge"]},{type:"architectureCard",title:"Social Graph Store",description:'Stores billions of directed follow edges with fast "who follows X" and "who does X follow" lookups. Sharded by user id; hot follower lists are cached.',icon:"share",tags:["graph","edges","sharded"]}]},{id:"fan-out-strategies",title:"Fan-out: Write vs Read",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"This is the heart of the design. There are two pure strategies and one hybrid that real systems use."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Fan-out-on-write vs fan-out-on-read.",columns:["Fan-out on write (push)","Fan-out on read (pull)"],rows:[{feature:"Read latency",values:["Fast (precomputed)","Slow (merge at read)"]},{feature:"Write cost",values:["High (N writes/post)","Low (1 write/post)"]},{feature:"Good for",values:["Normal users","Celebrities / inactive users"]},{feature:"Storage",values:["Large (per-user lists)","Small"]},{feature:"Freshness",values:[!0,!0]},{feature:"Celebrity-safe",values:[!1,!0]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"The hybrid (what X actually does)",body:"Use **fan-out-on-write** for the vast majority of users. For a small set of **high-fan-out accounts** (e.g. > ~1M followers), do **not** push their posts; instead, at read time, the Timeline Service pulls those accounts' recent posts and **merges** them into the reader's precomputed timeline. This bounds write amplification while keeping reads fast."},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Also skip fan-out to inactive users",body:"Pushing into the timelines of users who have not logged in for months is wasted work. Skip them on write and rebuild their timeline on-demand when they return. This dramatically cuts fan-out volume."}]},{id:"api-design",title:"API Design",blocks:[{type:"apiTable",title:"Core endpoints",endpoints:[{method:"POST",path:"/v1/tweets",description:"Create a post",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/tweets/{id}",description:"Fetch a single post",auth:!1},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/timeline/home",description:"Ranked home timeline (cursor-paginated)",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/timeline/user/{id}",description:"A user's own posts (profile)",auth:!1},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/users/{id}/follow",description:"Follow a user",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/tweets/{id}/like",description:"Like a post",auth:!0},{method:"POST",path:"/v1/tweets/{id}/repost",description:"Repost / retweet",auth:!0},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/search?q=",description:"Search posts and users",auth:!1},{method:"GET",path:"/v1/trends",description:"Trending topics by region",auth:!1}]},{type:"markdown",value:"Timelines use **cursor-based pagination** (not offset) so paging is stable as new posts arrive. The cursor encodes the position in the timeline (e.g. a Snowflake ID), avoiding the duplicate/skip problems of offset paging on a constantly-growing list."},{type:"code",language:"json",filename:"home-timeline-response.json",highlightLines:[2,14],code:`{
  "cursor": { "top": "1745...001", "bottom": "1745...032" },
  "items": [
    {
      "id": "1745928374650000001",
      "author": { "id": "u_42", "handle": "@ada", "verified": true },
      "text": "Shipping the new timeline ranker today \u{1F680}",
      "createdAt": 1735689600000,
      "metrics": { "likes": 1280, "reposts": 342, "replies": 56, "views": 91000 },
      "media": [],
      "rankScore": 0.873
    }
  ],
  "hasMore": true
}`}]},{id:"database-design",title:"Database Design",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Polyglot persistence: posts in a wide-column store, the timeline as Redis lists of IDs, the graph in a sharded edge store, counts in dedicated counters, and search in an inverted index."},{type:"code",language:"sql",filename:"tweets.cql",highlightLines:[3,9],code:`-- Posts: partition by author for fast "user timeline" reads;
-- the id is a Snowflake (time-sortable) so clustering gives order.
CREATE TABLE tweets (
  author_id  bigint,
  tweet_id   bigint,        -- Snowflake: 41-bit ms timestamp + machine + seq
  text       text,
  media_ref  text,
  reply_to   bigint,
  PRIMARY KEY ((author_id), tweet_id)
) WITH CLUSTERING ORDER BY (tweet_id DESC);

-- Follow edges, queryable in both directions via two tables.
CREATE TABLE followers (user_id bigint, follower_id bigint,
  PRIMARY KEY ((user_id), follower_id));     -- who follows me
CREATE TABLE following (user_id bigint, followee_id bigint,
  PRIMARY KEY ((user_id), followee_id));     -- who I follow`},{type:"table",caption:"Data store chosen per workload.",headers:["Data","Store","Why"],rows:[["Posts (source of truth)","Manhattan / Cassandra","Write-heavy, partition by author, AP"],["Home timelines","Redis (lists of IDs)","Precomputed, fast reads, capped length"],["Social graph","Sharded graph/edge store","Billions of edges, bidirectional lookups"],["Counts (likes/reposts/views)","Sharded counters / Redis","High write rate, approximate ok"],["Search index","Elasticsearch (Earlybird)","Full-text + recency ranking"],["Media","Blob store + CDN","Large, immutable, cacheable"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Why Snowflake IDs",body:'A 64-bit **Snowflake** ID embeds a millisecond timestamp, so IDs are roughly time-sortable and globally unique without a central sequence. This makes "newest first" ordering and cursor pagination trivial across a sharded store.'}]},{id:"caching-strategy",title:"Caching Strategy",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The timeline cache *is* the product: each user's home timeline is a Redis list of the most recent ~800 tweet IDs. Tweet content, user profiles, and counts sit in a separate cache so hydration is a batch of fast key lookups."},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"Store IDs, not content",body:"Timelines hold **tweet IDs**, not full tweets. A single tweet (especially a viral one) is stored once and referenced from millions of timelines. Hydration fetches the content + author + counts in a batched multi-get, keeping the timeline cache tiny and avoiding duplicated storage."},{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"TimelineService.java",highlightLines:[7,8,9,10,11],code:`@Service
public class TimelineService {

  private final RedisTimeline timelines;   // per-user list of tweet IDs
  private final TweetCache tweets;          // id -> hydrated tweet
  private final CelebrityReader celebrities;

  public List<Tweet> home(long userId, Cursor cursor) {
    List<Long> ids = timelines.range(userId, cursor, 50);   // precomputed
    List<Tweet> base = tweets.multiGet(ids);                // batch hydrate
    List<Tweet> merged = celebrities.mergeInto(base, userId); // pull path
    return ranker.rank(merged, userId);                     // ML ranking
  }
}`},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Caching best practices applied here",practices:["**Cap timeline length** (~800 IDs); older posts are reconstructed from the tweet store on demand.","**Batch hydrate** tweet content with multi-get to minimize round-trips.","**Cache hot tweets and profiles** separately so a viral post is one cache entry.","**Add TTL + jitter** to avoid synchronized expiry stampedes.","**Rebuild lazily**: if a returning user's timeline was evicted, recompute from follows."]}]},{id:"communication-flow",title:"Communication Flow",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The full lifecycle of posting a tweet and a follower reading it:"},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Post (write fan-out) then read (hydrate + merge).",definition:`sequenceDiagram
  participant A as Author
  participant T as Tweet Svc
  participant K as Kafka
  participant F as Fan-out Worker
  participant R as Redis Timelines
  participant U as Follower
  participant TL as Timeline Svc
  A->>T: POST /tweets
  T->>T: persist + assign Snowflake id
  T-->>A: 201 Created
  T->>K: emit tweet.created
  K->>F: consume
  F->>F: lookup followers (skip celebs/inactive)
  F->>R: LPUSH id into each follower timeline
  U->>TL: GET /timeline/home
  TL->>R: range of tweet IDs
  TL->>TL: hydrate + merge celebrity posts + rank
  TL-->>U: ranked page`},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Write returns before fan-out finishes",body:"The author gets a `201` as soon as the post is durably stored and the event is queued. Fan-out happens **asynchronously** via Kafka so a slow or huge fan-out never blocks the poster. Followers see the post within seconds."}]},{id:"ranking",title:"Timeline Ranking",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Modern timelines are **ranked**, not purely chronological. After assembling candidate posts (from follows + a small amount of out-of-network recommendation), a lightweight ML model scores each by predicted engagement, recency, author affinity, and media type, then sorts."},{type:"bestPractices",title:"Ranking pipeline stages",practices:["**Candidate generation**: in-network (follows) + out-of-network (recommended) posts.","**Feature hydration**: engagement counts, author affinity, recency, content type.","**Scoring**: a model predicts P(engagement) per candidate.","**Heuristics & filtering**: dedupe, demote low-quality/abuse, diversify authors.","**Mixing**: interleave ads/notifications, cap consecutive posts per author."]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Keep a chronological fallback",body:'Always offer a "Latest" (reverse-chronological) timeline. It is cheaper, fully predictable, and a safe fallback if the ranking service degrades \u2014 graceful degradation over a broken feed.'}]},{id:"search-trends",title:"Search & Trending",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Search is powered by an **inverted index** (Elasticsearch / Twitter's Earlybird) optimized for recency \u2014 newest matching posts first. Trends are computed from a streaming count of hashtags/phrases over a sliding time window, scored by **velocity** (acceleration), not raw volume, so genuinely *emerging* topics surface."},{type:"code",language:"python",filename:"trending.py",code:`# Streaming trend detection over a sliding window.
# Score by acceleration so newly-spiking topics beat always-popular ones.
def trend_score(term, window):
    recent = count(term, last="5m")
    baseline = count(term, last="1h") / 12      # per-5m expected
    velocity = (recent - baseline) / max(baseline, 1)
    return velocity * log(recent + 1)            # dampen tiny-volume noise`},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Trends are an abuse target",body:"Bots try to manufacture trends. Defenses: de-duplicate by account, weight by account quality/age, cap per-account contribution, and filter spam clusters before scoring."}]},{id:"scaling-strategy",title:"Scaling Strategy",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Hybrid fan-out**: push for normal users, pull-and-merge for celebrities; skip inactive users.","**Async fan-out via Kafka** so writes never block on large follower sets.","**Store IDs, hydrate on read** so viral posts are stored once, referenced everywhere.","**Shard everything by user id**: timelines, graph, posts, counters.","**Approximate counts** with sharded counters; exactness is not required.","**Autoscale stateless services** (tweet, timeline, fan-out) on RPS + lag."]},{type:"callout",variant:"info",title:"The celebrity problem, quantified",body:"A user with 100M followers posting would create 100M timeline writes. Doing that on write for even a handful of such accounts overwhelms the fan-out tier and Redis. The hybrid model trades a little read-time merge cost for a massive reduction in write amplification."}]},{id:"consistency",title:"Consistency",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"Feeds are **eventually consistent**: a new post propagates to follower timelines within seconds, and that is fine. Posts themselves are durable immediately on write. Engagement counts are eventually-consistent approximations aggregated from sharded counters."},{type:"featureComparison",caption:"Consistency expectations by data type.",columns:["Strong","Eventual"],rows:[{feature:"Post durability (accepted post)",values:[!0,!1]},{feature:"Home timeline freshness",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Like / repost counts",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"Follow graph view",values:[!1,!0]},{feature:"User profile / handle",values:[!0,!1]}]},{type:"callout",variant:"tip",title:"Read-your-own-writes",body:"A poster should see their own tweet immediately. Achieve this by injecting the just-created post into the author's own timeline synchronously (or reading their user-timeline first), even before async fan-out completes for others."}]},{id:"availability",title:"Availability",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The read path must stay up even when sub-systems degrade. Each dependency has a **fallback**: if ranking is down, serve the chronological timeline; if the timeline cache misses, rebuild from the graph; if counts are unavailable, hide the number rather than error."},{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Graceful degradation",body:"A degraded timeline (chronological, no ranking, approximate counts) is far better than an error page. Never let a non-critical service (ranking, trends, counts) take down the core feed."},{type:"youtube",videoId:"wYk0xPP_P_8",title:"Designing a news feed / timeline (illustrative embed)"}]},{id:"partitioning",title:"Partitioning",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:'Posts partition by `author_id` (a profile is one fast read). Timelines partition by the **owning** user id. The graph partitions by user id with both follower and following lists. This keeps the common queries \u2014 "my timeline", "my profile", "who follows me" \u2014 to a single partition.'},{type:"callout",variant:"warning",title:"Avoid hot partitions",body:"A celebrity's follower list is enormous and read on every one of their posts \u2014 a hot partition. Mitigate by **caching follower lists**, **chunking** very large lists across partitions, and routing celebrity posts to the read-time merge path so they are not iterated on write."}]},{id:"sharding",title:"Sharding",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"All stores shard by a hash of the user id via consistent hashing, so adding capacity rebalances automatically. Redis timelines are sharded the same way; a user's entire timeline lives on one shard for a single-shard read."},{type:"mermaid",caption:"Consistent hashing of users to shards.",definition:`flowchart LR
  U1["user 42"] --> S1["Shard 1 (timeline + posts + edges)"]
  U2["user 1337"] --> S2["Shard 2"]
  U3["user 9001"] --> S3["Shard 3"]
  LB["Router (hash(user_id))"] --> S1 & S2 & S3`}]},{id:"replication",title:"Replication",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"The post store replicates each partition (RF=3, one per AZ) with quorum writes so a single AZ loss never drops an accepted post. Redis timelines run with replicas + persistence so a node failure does not blank out feeds. Data is replicated across regions and users are served from the nearest one."},{type:"prosCons",title:"Multi-region active-active",pros:["Survives a full region outage.","Lower read latency by serving the nearest region.","No idle cold-standby capacity."],cons:["Cross-region lag \u2192 brief timeline divergence.","Operationally complex (data + traffic steering).","Higher infrastructure cost."]}]},{id:"fault-tolerance",title:"Fault Tolerance",blocks:[{type:"bestPractices",practices:["**Persist before ACK** so an accepted post is never lost on crash.","**Idempotent fan-out** keyed on `(follower_id, tweet_id)` so retries are safe.","**Circuit breakers + timeouts** on ranking, counts, and trends.","**Fallback to chronological** timeline when ranking is unavailable.","**Rebuild timelines lazily** from the graph if a cache shard is lost.","**Backpressure** on the fan-out tier during post spikes (breaking news)."]},{type:"expandable",title:"Example: idempotent fan-out worker",blocks:[{type:"code",language:"java",filename:"FanoutWorker.java",code:`public void onTweetCreated(TweetEvent e) {
  if (isHighFanout(e.authorId())) return;       // celebrities: read-time merge
  for (long follower : graph.activeFollowers(e.authorId())) {
    // LPUSH is naturally idempotent if we dedupe on tweet id within the
    // capped list; trim keeps the timeline bounded.
    redis.lpushCappedDedup("tl:" + follower, e.tweetId(), 800);
  }
}`}]}]},{id:"trade-offs",title:"Trade-offs",blocks:[{type:"table",caption:"Key decisions and what they cost.",headers:["Decision","Gain","Cost"],rows:[["Hybrid fan-out","Fast reads + bounded writes","Two code paths to maintain"],["Fan-out on write (normal users)","Low read latency","High write amplification, storage"],["Store IDs not content","Tiny timelines, no dup storage","Extra hydration step on read"],["Ranked timeline","More engagement","Compute cost, complexity, less predictable"],["Eventual consistency","Availability + scale","Brief staleness, approximate counts"],["Snowflake IDs","Sortable, decentralized","Clock-skew handling needed"]]}]},{id:"technology-choices",title:"Technology Choices",blocks:[{type:"markdown",value:"A representative slice of the stack and the role each plays:"},{type:"table",headers:["Concern","Technology"],rows:[["Post store","Manhattan (Twitter) / Cassandra"],["Timeline cache","Redis"],["Eventing / fan-out","Apache Kafka"],["Search","Elasticsearch / Earlybird"],["ID generation","Snowflake"],["Counters","Sharded counters / Redis"],["Media","Blob store + CDN"],["Ranking","ML scoring service (e.g. TF/Torch)"]]},{type:"callout",variant:"note",title:"Why precompute timelines?",body:"Reads outnumber writes ~100:1. Paying a one-time fan-out cost on write to make the (far more frequent) read a single cache lookup is the classic **read-optimized** trade \u2014 you do expensive work on the rare path to make the common path cheap."},{type:"code",language:"yaml",filename:"fanout-service.deploy.yaml",code:`service: fanout-worker
strategy: rolling
regions: [us-east-1, us-west-2, eu-west-1]
autoscaling:
  metric: kafka_consumer_lag
  target: 10000             # messages of lag before scaling out
  min: 20
  max: 600
healthCheck:
  path: /health
  unhealthyThreshold: 3`}]},{id:"interview-questions",title:"Interview Questions",blocks:[{type:"interviewQa",items:[{question:"How do you build the home timeline at scale?",answer:"Precompute it with **fan-out-on-write**: when a user posts, push the tweet ID into each follower's Redis timeline asynchronously via Kafka. Reads then become a fast list lookup + batch hydration. For high-follower accounts, switch to **fan-out-on-read** (pull + merge) to avoid write amplification. This hybrid is the standard answer."},{question:"How do you handle a celebrity with 100M followers?",answer:"Do **not** fan out their posts on write \u2014 that is 100M writes per tweet. Mark them as high-fan-out and, at read time, the Timeline Service **pulls** their recent posts and merges them into each reader's precomputed timeline. You pay a small merge cost on read instead of a catastrophic cost on write."},{question:"Why store tweet IDs in timelines instead of full tweets?",answer:"Deduplication and size. A viral tweet is stored once and referenced by millions of timelines as just an ID. On read you batch-hydrate IDs into content. This keeps timeline storage tiny and means an edit/delete updates one place."},{question:"How do you paginate an ever-growing timeline?",answer:"Use **cursor-based pagination** keyed on a time-sortable Snowflake ID, not offset. New posts arriving at the top do not shift the cursor, so users never see duplicates or skips while scrolling."},{question:"How is trending computed?",answer:"Stream hashtag/phrase counts over a sliding window and score by **velocity (acceleration)**, not raw volume, so emerging topics beat perennially-popular ones. Apply anti-abuse: dedupe by account, weight by account quality, cap per-account contribution."},{question:"What happens when the ranking service fails?",answer:"Fall back to the **reverse-chronological** timeline. It is cheaper and fully predictable, so the user still gets a usable feed \u2014 graceful degradation rather than an error."}]}]},{id:"references",title:"References",blocks:[{type:"references",items:[{label:"The Infrastructure Behind Twitter: Scale",url:"https://blog.twitter.com/engineering/en_us/topics/infrastructure/2017/the-infrastructure-behind-twitter-scale",source:"Twitter Engineering"},{label:"Twitter's Recommendation Algorithm (open source)",url:"https://blog.twitter.com/engineering/en_us/topics/open-source/2023/twitter-recommendation-algorithm",source:"Twitter Engineering"},{label:"Manhattan: Twitter's distributed database",url:"https://blog.twitter.com/engineering/en_us/a/2014/manhattan-our-real-time-multi-tenant-distributed-database-for-twitter-scale",source:"Twitter Engineering"},{label:"Snowflake: distributed ID generation",url:"https://blog.twitter.com/engineering/en_us/a/2010/announcing-snowflake",source:"Twitter Engineering"},{label:"Earlybird: real-time search at Twitter",url:"https://blog.twitter.com/engineering/en_us/a/2011/the-engineering-behind-twitter-s-new-search-experience",source:"Twitter Engineering"}]}]},{id:"summary",title:"Summary",blocks:[{type:"callout",variant:"summary",title:"Key takeaways",body:`1. **The home timeline is the core problem** \u2014 solve it with a **hybrid fan-out**: push for normal users, pull-and-merge for celebrities, skip inactive users.
2. **Read-optimize**: reads beat writes ~100:1, so precompute timelines and make reads a single cache lookup + batch hydration.
3. **Store IDs, not content** so viral posts are stored once and referenced everywhere.
4. **Embrace eventual consistency** for feeds and approximate counts to maximize availability and scale.
5. **Rank with a fallback**: ML-ranked timeline for engagement, reverse-chronological as the safe degradation path.`}]}]},a=t;export{a as default};
